{ Alekhine - Euwe, 1922 }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 (2. Bf4!? g6 3. Nc3! { One main reason to play the London but with 2. Bf4 is that this move order prevents the KID setups. Unless d5 is played right now, white has a perfectly reasonable Pirc with e4 coming next. } 3... d5! $10 (3... Bg7?! 4. e4! $14)) 2... g6 3. Bf4 { This London move order lacks zing. Much better is c4 and Nc3, re-entering the typical KID. } (3. c4!?) 3... Bg7 4. Nbd2 (4. Nc3?! d5 $10 { In this line, the f3 knight might be misplaced. }) 4... c5 5. e3 d6 6. c3 Nc6 7. h3 { Preserving the dark-squared bishop } 7... O-O (7... cxd4!? 8. exd4 e5! { Taking the fight to white ASAP. } 9. dxe5!? (9. Be3!? O-O $15) 9... dxe5 10. Bg5 O-O $15) 8. Bc4 Re8?! { This move aims for e5, but it weakens f7, and is too slow. An expansion on the queenside with a6 and b5 makes more sense. } (8... cxd4!? 9. exd4 e5! { Now it really is called for. } 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nxe5?! (11. Bg5!? e4! $15) 11... Qe7! 12. Qe2 Nh5 13. Nd3 Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Nxf4+ 15. Nxf4 Re8+ $15) 9. O-O e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5?! (10... dxe5! 11. Ng5!? (11. Bh2!? { Alekhine's suggestion. } 11... Be6 12. Bxe6 Rxe6 13. Qb3 $14) 11... Re7 (11... exf4 12. Bxf7+ Kh8 13. Bxe8 Qxe8 14. exf4 h6 15. Re1 Qg8 16. Nge4 $14) 12. Bh2 $14 { Black looks awkward, but the central control should give black enough play here. }) 11. Bxe5! { Not losing time to hammer at the light squares! } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gf3g5] } 11... dxe5 12. Ng5! { Giving up the bishop pair, but ruining black's pawn structure, white now transitions into a good knight vs bad bishop endgame almost by force. } { [%csl Gf7] } 12... Be6?! (12... Re7!? 13. Nde4! (13. Qb3?! Qxd2?? (13... Qc7! $10) 14. Rad1! $18) 13... Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Bf5 15. Nd6 $16) (12... Rf8?! 13. Nde4! $16 { [%cal Ge4d6] }) 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Nde4 { A knight will now stay on e4 forever. The d knight makes more sense to trade off the queens too. } 14... Nxe4 (14... Qb6 15. Qb3) 15. Qxd8 (15. Nxe4!? $16 { Keeping queens on the board means black's king safety remains a concern as well. }) 15... Rexd8 16. Nxe4 { Covers the entrance square on d2 and a good knight vs bad bishop endgame is achieved. White will easily win due to black's structural damage. } { [%csl Gd2] } 16... b6 17. Rfd1 Kf7 18. Kf1 Ke7 19. c4 { The pawns belong on light squares, but I don't see why this is more important than Ke2. } 19... h6 20. Ke2 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 $18 { Black has a hopeless endgame ahead of them because this knight is a monster and the bishop is terrible. White can infiltrate on the kingside and target g6/h5 if necessary. } 21... Rd8?! (21... Rb8!? { Played in the actual game. }) 22. Rxd8 Kxd8 23. h4! $18 { Is an objectively winning endgame, analyzed as problem 111 of this book, so this game must be the aforementioned Alekhine - Euwe, 1922. } 23... Ke7 24. g4 Kd7 25. g5 hxg5 (25... h5) 26. hxg5 Ke7 27. b3 Kd7 28. Nc3 Ke7 29. Kd3 Kd7 30. Ke4 Ke7 31. Ne2 Kd7 32. Nc1 Ke7 33. Nd3 Kd6 34. f4! Bh8!? (34... exf4?! 35. Nxf4 $18 { [%cal Gf4g6] }) 35. fxe5+ Ke7 36. b4! $18 *


