1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5 Bg7 4. Nbd2 d5 5. e3 Ne4?! { The knight jumps into the center, but it can be captured by white's poorly placed knight freeing white to activate their queenside majority. } (5... O-O 6. Be2 c5 $10) 6. Nxe4 dxe4 7. Nd2 c5 8. c3 { c3 stays solid in the center, but the queenside majority is still nascently waiting in the background. } 8... cxd4? { Releasing the tension in the center means that white safely has a 4 on 2 queenside majority vs a crippled 5 vs 3 kingside majority for black. } 9. exd4! (9. cxd4?! Qa5! 10. Bf4 Nc6 11. a3 (11. Be2?! e5! $15) 11... O-O 12. b4?! (12. Bg3! e5 (12... Rd8?! 13. Rc1! e5 14. Rc5! $14) 13. b4 Qd8 14. d5! Qxd5 15. Bc4 $10) 12... Qf5 13. Bg3 Rd8 14. Rc1 e5! $15) 9... Qd5 10. Be3 O-O 11. Be2!? { Stays out of the way of the c4 push (which white wants to make to get the majority rolling). } (11. Bc4! Qf5!? (11... Qc6!? 12. d5 Qc7 13. Bb3 $16 { [%cal Gd2e4] }) 12. Qb1! b5 13. Bb3 Bb7 14. Bc2 $16 { [%csl Ge4] }) 11... e5! { Attacks the pawn chain and tries to open up the position at a time when white's king is still in the center. } 12. Qb3 (12. c4?! { Too early } 12... Qd8 13. d5 f5 $10 { Black's kingside play faster than white's queenside play. The knight is misplaced and should be on c3 now. }) (12. dxe5!? Qxe5 13. Qa4 f5 14. O-O-O $14 { [%cal Ge3d4] }) 12... Qxb3 13. Nxb3 f5 { Tries to get rolling with the kingside majority, but why not take a time-out and get rid of the doubled pawn? } (13... Nc6!? { Engine suggestion } 14. d5 Ne7 15. O-O-O Nf5 16. Bc5 Rd8 $10 { b6 is coming, winning the bishop pair. }) 14. d5!? { Pushing through and trying to claim the g7 bishop is bad. Honestly though, black's center is imposing. } (14. dxe5!? Bxe5 15. O-O-O Nc6 (15... f4?! 16. Bc5! $14) 16. Bc4+ Kg7 17. Rhe1 $14) 14... b6 15. Rd1?! (15. O-O!? Nd7 16. Rfd1 $10 { The correct rook. }) (15. a4!? $10 { Justifies the rook on a1. } { [%cal Ga4a5] }) 15... Bb7 16. Bg5?! { Constantly moving this bishop back and forth is not to be recommended. } (16. c4!? Nd7 (16... f4?! 17. Bc1 $14 { Black would prefer to have the bishop on f5 in this structure now. }) 17. c5! f4 18. c6 fxe3 19. fxe3 Bc8 20. cxd7 Bxd7 $10) 16... Bf6?! { Don't trade away this "bad" bishop! When the kingside pawn storm starts rolling, you'll want all your pieces out there in order to generate play on the kingside. } (16... Nd7 17. O-O Rac8 $15 { Simple and good. }) 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. c4 Nd7 19. O-O $10 { White's majority is more advanced, but black can quickly play f4 and e3, so it's unclear if anyone is actually pushing through faster. However, when e3 is played, fxe3 can come and double black's pawns. So it's not so easy. Roughly equal final position. } *


