{ Pam - David Preuss, 1998. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c4!? { White goes for a Maroczy bind in a position where his light squared bishop is outside the pawn chain. If he can keep pieces on the board, this is fine, but it seems likely that bishop will have to trade itself off. } 4... a6 5. Ba4 Qc7?! { As opposed to in the e6 Sicilians, the queen does not belong on this square because the h2-b8 diagonal is blocked. } (5... Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. O-O Be7 8. d4 cxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. Rd1 $14) 6. Nc3 e6 7. O-O!? (7. d4!? cxd4 8. Qxd4 $14 { Would be my preference now that the queen cannot be hit. }) 7... Nf6 8. Qe2 (8. d4!? { Again does make sense. } 8... cxd4 9. Qxd4 { Hansen, Eric - Iniyan, P., 1/2-1/2, Portugal Open 2019, https://lichess.org/aegoDMGP }) 8... Be7 9. d4 { White finally gets on with it. But the queen was probably stronger on d4 than the knight. } (9. d3!? $10 { A slower way to play, but I'd prefer to already have in f4 in this position as white. }) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. Be3 Nb6? { Terrible move. It's a one move threat and instead of activating the light squared bishop with b6-Bb7, black is admitting that the piece will not ever be active. } (11... Ne5 $10) 12. Bb3 e5? { The hole on d5 means that now white can transition into a positional game with a huge grip on the center. f3, Rc1, Rd1, and Nd5 will allow white to take control of the game for a long time. Either this move works (because Ng4 is good), or loses the game immediately. } 13. Nf5!? (13. Nc2!? Ng4 14. Bxb6! Qxb6 15. Nd5 Qd8 16. f3 Nf6 17. Nce3 $16) 13... Bxf5 14. exf5 { White now controls the central breaks, but doesn't have as strong a grip on the light squares as in the other line. Instead, white goes for an attack on the kingside, spearheaded by this f5 pawn. } 14... Rac8 { The c4 pawn will now fall by force, but does white have something on the kingside? } 15. g4?! { Rushing into it, but I suppose c4 can't be captured so quickly. } (15. Rac1!? $16 { Now the c pawn can never be taken. g4 can happen later. } 15... h6!? $14 (15... Nxc4?? 16. Bxc4 Qxc4 17. Qxc4 Rxc4 18. Nd5! Rxc1 19. Nxe7+ Kh8 20. Rxc1 $18)) 15... h6 { Creating a hook near the king, but black possibly has it all under control. } (15... Nxc4?? 16. g5 Nxe3 (16... Ne8? 17. Nd5! $18) 17. gxf6 Nxf1? (17... Nxf5!? 18. Nd5! Qd8 19. fxe7 Nxe7 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Rad1 $16) 18. Nd5!! { Wins the game on the spot. } (18. fxe7?? Qxe7 19. Rxf1 { An interesting line where black can end all kingside threats and go for a game based on central expansion. Unfortunately, the d5 hole now rests firmly in white's hands. } 19... Qg5+ 20. Kh1 Qxf5 $10) 18... Qd7 19. fxe7 Rfe8 20. Qg4 { [%cal Gd5f6] } 20... Kh8 21. Rxf1 $18) (15... Kh8?! 16. g5 Ng8 17. Rac1 $16) 16. h4 Nh7 { Black simply puts a stop to everything and says "I still will have the c4 pawn." } 17. g5!? { Meanwhile white says "I still have a kingside attack." My first reaction is that I don't believe this for white, but the threats on the g and h files come quickly.
Yet this is all possible because the piece on g5 cannot be defended with f6 - allowing death by LSB after c5+! } 17... hxg5 18. hxg5 Bxg5 (18... Nxg5?! 19. Qg4 Nh7 20. Kh2 $18 { [%cal Gf1g1] }) 19. Bxg5 Nxg5 20. Qg4 { Black is up a pawn and white's king is very exposed. Yet black has no pieces to attack the white king, so the h file does actually prove crucial. } 20... Qe7?! { This is not the optimal way to defend the knight. } (20... Nh7! 21. Kg2?! (21. Rad1!? Nf6 22. Qg5 $10) 21... Nf6 { Black has no issues at all and can finally take the c4 pawn with a huge center. } 22. Qh4 { [%cal Gf1h1,Gh4h8] } 22... Rfd8 23. Rh1 Kf8 24. Qh8+? Ke7 $17 25. Qxg7?? Rg8) (20... f6?? 21. c5+ $18) 21. Kg2! { Bringing the rooks to the h file. } 21... Nh7?! (21... Rc5!? 22. Rh1 f6 23. Rh5! Kf7 24. Ne4! Ke8 (24... Nxe4?? 25. Qg6+ Kg8 26. Rah1 $18) 25. Nxc5 $16) (21... f6?? 22. c5+! $18) (21... e4!? 22. Rh1 g6 23. fxg6 Rc5 24. gxf7+ Rxf7 25. Rag1 $14 { It's hard to believe black is OK here, but white's king is just as vulnerable as black's. }) 22. Rh1!? (22. Ne4! $16 { A more reasonable way to bring pieces into the game I think. Qg5 is prevented. }) 22... d5? { Black completely panics trying to prevent Ne4. } (22... Qg5!? 23. Qxg5 Nxg5 24. Rh5! { The knight still has nowhere good to go! } 24... Nh7 25. Rah1 $18) 23. cxd5 (23. Rxh7!! { And it doesn't even work! } 23... Kxh7 24. Rh1+ Kg8 25. Qh5! $18) 23... Qg5 24. Qxg5! Nxg5 25. Rh5! { Unbelievably, black's knight is trapped on g5. } 25... f6!? { One of a few attempts to keep the knight protected. White is completely winning here. } (25... Nc4?! 26. Rxg5 $18) (25... Nh7!? 26. Rah1! Rfd8 (26... Nf6?? 27. Rh8#) 27. Rxh7 Kf8 28. f6! gxf6 29. d6! { [%cal Gh7f7] } 29... Nc4!? (29... Rd7!? 30. Rh8+ Kg7 31. R1h7+ Kg6 32. Rh6+ Kg7 33. R8h7+ Kf8 34. Ne4! $18) 30. Bxc4! Rxc4 31. Rh8+ Kg7 32. Rxd8 $18) 26. d6+ Rf7!? (26... Nf7!? 27. Rah1! Nc4 28. d7 Rc7 29. Nd5! $18) 27. Rah1! Kf8 28. Rh8# { White forced through an attack with the only justification being black's poor light square control in the center. Black failed to trade off pieces and instead marooned half their forces on the queenside going after a c pawn they never captured.. } *


