1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 { The richter-rauzer variation } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nd7? { As black you don't have time to reposition your pieces so much when you haven't developed anything yet. Black would have done much better to play e6, Be7 and 0-0 immediately. } (7... e6 { The main line. } 8. O-O-O Be7 9. f4 h6 (9... Bd7!? 10. Nf3 b5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Kb1 $10) 10. Bh4 Nxe4?? (10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 11... O-O $14) 11. Bxe7 Nxd2 12. Bxd8 Nxf1 13. Nxc6! Ne3 14. Rxd6 bxc6 15. Bb6 Nc4 { [%cal Gc4d6,Gc4b6] } 16. Rd8+ $18) 8. Be2 g6 { Black continues with their plan to fianchetto the bishop without taking structural damage, but white's active pieces infiltrate quickly. } (8... h6!? 9. Ne6! (9. Be3!? $14) 9... fxe6?? (9... Qa5!? 10. Nxf8 hxg5 11. Nxd7 Bxd7 $10) 10. Bh5+ g6 11. Bxg6#) 9. Nd5! f6?? { Never play f6... it's so weakening and we immediately see white take advantage of the light squared weaknesses to win at least a queen. } (9... Bg7!? { Probably still best, but this loses almost immediately. } 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Nxe7 f6 12. Nxc8 fxg5 13. Nxd6+ $18) (9... Nxd4!? 10. Qxd4 $16 { [%csl Gh8] }) (9... Nc5!? 10. O-O-O $16 { There's no chance that black can get away with snagging e4 without further development. }) 10. Ne6! Qa5 11. Ndc7+ Kf7 12. Nd8+! Kg7!? (12... Kg8!? 13. Bc4+ d5 14. Bxd5+ e6 (14... Qxd5 15. Qxd5+ e6 16. Qxe6+ Kg7 17. Qf7#) 15. Bxe6+ Kg7 16. Bh6# { A bloody mess in every variation. }) (12... Nxd8?? 13. Qxa5 $18) 13. Ne8+! (13. Bh6+!? Kg8 14. Bc4+ d5 15. Bxd5+ e6 16. Bxe6# { A similar mate can occur. }) 13... Kg8 14. Bc4+ d5 15. Bxd5+ e6 16. Bxe6# *


