1. e4 Nc6 2. d4 (2. Nf3!? e5!? (2... d5?! 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qa5 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. a3 a6?? (6... O-O-O 7. Rb1 $14 { [%cal Gb2b4] }) 7. b4!! Nxb4 8. axb4 Qxa1 9. Bxd7+ Kxd7 10. Nd4! $18 { Nb3 trapping the queen is unstoppable. }) (2... d6?! 3. d4 Bg4 4. d5! Ne5? (4... Nb8 $14) 5. Nxe5! Bxd1 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 a6!? (7... Qa5+!? 8. Nc3 O-O-O 9. Nc4! Qc7 10. Nd5! $16) 8. c7+ axb5 9. cxd8=Q+ Rxd8 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Kxd1 $16) 3. Bb5 $10) 2... e5 { I personally never believed in this Nimzowitch defense. You give up the center in the hopes of counterattacking on the wings. } 3. d5 Nce7 4. c4 Ng6 5. Bd3?! { Yes the bishop defends the e4 pawn, but it is literally the worst possible bishop. A more natural Nc3, Nf3, or Be2 makes more sense. } 5... Bb4+ { This check doesn't accomplish anything. White wanted to develop the knight to c3 anyway. } 6. Nc3 Nf6 (6... Bxc3+!? 7. bxc3 d6 $10 { Playing against the doubled pawns is also possible, but black is a mile away from achieving Nc5. }) 7. Bd2?! { The bishop clearly belongs on e3, not d2, to get in the c5 break. Ne2 is better if you want to avoid any doubled pawns. } (7. Ne2! $14) 7... O-O 8. Nf3 Bxc3? { Now it makes even less sense to give up this bishop. } (8... d6 $10) 9. Bxc3 Nf4?? { Hanging the e pawn after giving up the bishop pair. Oof. } (9... d6 $14) 10. O-O?? { White's forgetting the main rule of chess: take free stuff. } (10. Bxe5! Nxg2+ 11. Kf1! (11. Kd2!? $16 { And white has a strong attack on black's king using the open g file and the centralized bishops. }) 11... d6 12. Bg3 $18) 10... Nxd3?! { Trading a good knight for a bad bishop. At least it gets rid of the bishop pair, but it's not like that bishop was going anywhere in the meantime. } (10... d6 $14 { Clearly an improvement. }) 11. Qxd3 d6 12. h3?! $10 { An unnecessary kingside weakness. There is no pin to be feared, and the important square to cover is f4, not g4.
Overall, I would rate white as a 1400 player, as most of his moves made sense, and he got a strong center. He didn't play precisely though in order to maximize his advantage. I would rate black as a 1100 player. He knew the first few moves of an opening, but then proceeded to trade every good piece he had for white's bad pieces. None of black's trades made positional sense. } *


