1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 cxd4?! { Releasing the tension only allows white to place their knight on a better square. } 6. cxd4 Qb6 7. Nc3 Nge7 8. Na4?! { One move threat. The knight doesn't belong on a4, and would rather be back on c6 (or b5!), so this just pushes the queen to a better square. } (8. Bd3!? Bd7 9. O-O! Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Nb5!? $10 { One of these interesting French gambit lines. }) 8... Qd8?! { A full retreat seems a bit unnecessary. } (8... Qc7!? $14 { Yes it's on an open file, but at least it further influences the center. } { [%cal Gc7e5,Gc6e5,Gf7f6,Ge7g6,Gg6e5,Gf6e5] }) 9. g4? { Terribly weakening on the kingside, and this pawn cannot be maintained on g4, trying to prevent Nf5. } (9. Bd3!? $14 { Normal and good. }) (9. a3!? Nf5 10. b4 $14 { [%cal Gc1b2] }) 9... Ng6?! { Missing a golden opportunity to tear down white's construction. } (9... h5! { Simply winning the f5 square for the knight, activating the rook, and taking over the game. } 10. g5 (10. h3?? hxg4 $19 { [%cal Gh8h1] }) 10... Nf5 $17) 10. Bd2?! { Mindlessly developing without recognizing that the center is about to come under heavy fire. } (10. Be3 $10 { A better square, now that Nf5 isn't hurting white. }) 10... f6!? { Blowing open the center before white has time to develop. } (10... Nh4!? 11. Nxh4 Qxh4 $15 { h5 is coming next, and white's center is undefended. }) 11. h4? { White simply cannot get away with time wasters like this. } (11. exf6!? Qxf6 $15 { Bd6, O-O, Bd7, Rac8, etc. Black has a lot of easy moves. }) 11... fxe5 (11... h5!? { Fighting fire with fire is also interesting. But this move would have been much better without including Ng6. }) 12. h5 Nge7? { Retreating and blocking all of black's own pieces from coming out. } (12... Nf4! { I thought this was the point of black's last move. } 13. dxe5 (13. Bxf4? exf4 $17) 13... Bb4 $15) 13. dxe5 { I can't see how black activates even a single piece. } 13... Bd7!? (13... Qc7!? 14. Bc3 Bd7 $14 { Probably transposes. }) 14. Nc5 Qc7 15. Ng5?? { Now white is using the fact that black cannot untangle to launch a full-on assault... except for one thing. } (15. Nxd7? Qxd7 $10 { Capturing this bad bishop would be a travesty. }) 15... Nd4!? { Missing the free e5 pawn, black jumps through hoops trying to defend e6. Yet this does threaten Qxc5 and Nc2+ if the knight moves, so maybe it works out to the same thing. } (15... Qxe5+! $16 { Obvious and good. Black needs to snag this pawn now in order to develop and defend e6. }) (15... Qc8?! { Too depressing to even consider, but I'm not sure I see the specific KO. h6 is coming to kick out the knight. }) 16. Rc1 Qxe5+ { Now black snags the free e pawn. } 17. Be3 Nec6 18. Nd3 Qf6!? { Avoids blocking the DSB. Other retreats seemed possible too. } (18... Qd6!? 19. f4 (19. Bf4? e5! $17) 19... Be7 $17) 19. f4 Bd6 { Black is finishing development, and ready to castle either direction. } 20. Nf3? { That knight was actually quite well placed on g5. Why not further develop with Bg2? } (20. Bg2!? { Preparing O-O. } { [%cal Ge1g1] } 20... h6 21. Nh3 O-O 22. O-O $15) 20... Nxf3+ 21. Qxf3 O-O-O?! { A dangerous move. Black dares white to take on a7. } (21... O-O! 22. g5 Qe7 $17 { Black's king is safer on the kingside. e5 is ready to roll, blowing open the center while black has a lead in development. } { [%cal Ge6e5] }) 22. Bxa7!? { It looks scary for black, but really it should be scary for white. Their king is still in the center, and e5 can be played very soon. } (22. Bg2!? Kb8 23. O-O $15 { White was probably not happy with the following position arising. }) 22... Bc7?! $17 { Black has the central pawns, the safer king, and more development. He should be doing fine, even though it seems unnecessary to have lost a7, and retreating the bishop to c7 hardly improves the position at all. } (22... e5! { Let's go already! e4 is a threat, so there's only one response. } 23. Qxd5 Rhe8! $17 { No way is white surviving this. }) *


