{ Know thy classics theme. When is Bh7+ good and when it is a useless check? }
1. e4 (1. d4 { Petrosian - Taimanov, 1955 shows when Bh7+ can be good vs when it means nothing. } 1... d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 Bb4 7. O-O O-O 8. Qc2 Bd6 9. b3 dxc4 10. bxc4 e5 11. Bb2 Re8 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 h6 14. Rad1 exd4 15. Bh7+! { The Petrosian check! } 15... Kh8 (15... Kf8 16. Rxd4 $16 { [%cal Gd4f4] }) 16. Rxd4! Bc5 17. Rf4 Qe7 18. Re4! Qf8 19. Rh4 f6 20. Bg6 Re7 21. Rh5 Bd6 22. Rd1 Be5 23. Ba3! c5 24. Nh4 $18 { [%cal Gg6h7,Gh4g6] }) 1... e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 Be7 4. Bc4 Nh6? (4... Nf6 5. e5 Nh5 $10) 5. d4 c6 6. Bxf4 d5 7. exd5 cxd5 8. Bb5+?! { This check accomplishes nothing as it allows black to develop normally. } (8. Bd3!? { The square the bishop actually belongs on. } 8... Nf5 9. O-O Nc6 10. c3 $14) 8... Nc6 9. O-O (9. Bxh6 gxh6 10. Nc3 $14 { Not too late to play against black's kingside pawn structure though. }) 9... Nf5 10. Nc3?! (10. c3 $10) 10... O-O 11. Qd2?! { This square accomplishes nothing. The queen is better on d1. I would prefer a Ne2-g3 maneuver immediately. } (11. Ne2 { [%cal Gg7g5,Gf5e3] } 11... a6 12. Bd3 Be6 13. Ng3 Nxg3 14. Bxg3 { [%cal Gc2c3,Gd1c2,Gc2h7] }) 11... Bf6 12. Ne2 Nd6 (12... Ncxd4? 13. Nexd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qb6 15. Be3! Bxd4 16. Bxd4 Qxb5 17. Rae1 $16) (12... Qb6!? $10) 13. Bd3 (13. Bxd6!? { Gives up the bishop but creates a strong center. } 13... Qxd6 14. c3) 13... Ne4 14. Qe1 Re8 (14... Qb6! $15 { [%cal Gb6g1,Gb6b2] }) 15. c3 a6?! { Why? } (15... Bf5 $15 { Obviously better. }) 16. Qb1?! { The queen keeps repositioning to bad squares. Why not an immediate Ng3? } (16. Ng3!? Nxg3? (16... Nc5!? 17. Qd2 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 $10 { But an attack is still brewing on the kingside. }) 17. Qxg3 $16) 16... Na5? (16... Bf5 $15 { Obviously better. }) 17. Ng3 Nxg3 18. Bxg3? (18. Bxh7+! Kh8 19. Bxg3!? { This was the point of Qb1, no? } (19. hxg3!? g6?? 20. Bxg6 fxg6 21. Qxg6 $18 { [%cal Gg1f2,Gf1h1] }) 19... g6?? 20. Bxg6 fxg6 21. Qxg6 $18 { [%cal Gg3e5] }) 18... h6 19. Be5 Be6 20. Qc2?! { Missing the Petrosian check and putting the queen on a worse square soon to be opposite the rook. } (20. Bxf6! Qxf6 21. Bh7+! { The Petrosian check is great here. } 21... Kh8 (21... Kf8? 22. Ne5! Qg5 23. Ng6+ Qxg6 24. Bxg6 $18) 22. Ne5 Qe7 23. Bg6! Rf8 24. Bxf7 Bxf7 25. Rxf7 $18 { [%cal Ge5g6] }) 20... Rc8? 21. Qf2? { Missing the Petrosian check once again. } (21. Bxf6! Qxf6 22. Bh7+! { Again the Petrosian check is winning. } 22... Kh8 (22... Kf8? 23. Ne5! Qg5 24. Ng6+ $18) 23. Ne5 Qe7 24. Bg6! Rf8 25. Bxf7 Bxf7 26. Rxf7 $18) 21... Nc4 { The knight is not bothering white. White can simply work around it and see to improve the rest of the pieces with Rae1 or Bf4-Rae1-Bc1 to stay most solid and maintain the bishop pair. } 22. Bxc4? { Giving away the good bishop for nothing. } (22. Bf4!? b5 23. Rae1 Qb6 24. Ne5 $14 { [%cal Gf4h6,Gb5b4] }) (22. Rae1!? $14) 22... Rxc4? (22... dxc4! $10 { Repairing the structure and preparing a minority attack. White's passed pawn isn't going anywhere. } { [%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4] }) 23. Nd2! { A double attack. } 23... Bxe5!? (23... Rc6?! 24. Bxf6 Qxf6 25. Qxf6 gxf6 26. Rxf6 $16) 24. Nxc4! Bxh2+ 25. Kxh2 dxc4 { In the game itself, white is still up the exchange (for a pawn), so should be winning with the passed d pawn and active rooks. But trading off every piece does not help the side trying to attack on the dark squares. } 26. Rae1 Qd7 27. Re3 Bd5?! { Black should be seeking to keep the rooks on the board. Now the redundant rook can be traded and white is clearly up the exchange. } 28. Rxe8+! Qxe8 29. Re1 Qd7 30. Qe3 Kf8 31. Qe5 f6 32. Qg3 Kf7! { No infiltration on the e file! } { [%csl Ge5,Ge6,Ge7,Ge8] } 33. Qh3?! { The rook alone cannot infiltrate down the e file. Trading queens without further opening up the position makes white's life much harder. } (33. Kg1!? Bc6 34. Qf4 Bd5 35. Re3 Bc6 36. Qb8!? $16 { Eventually white will break through because black's king is so weak. }) 33... Qxh3+ 34. Kxh3 Be6+ 35. Kg3 Bd5 36. Kf2 Be6 37. g3 Bd5 38. Ke3 Ke6 39. Rb1 (39. Kf4+!? Kf7! (39... Kd6?! 40. Kf5! $18 { White infiltrates the position. }) 40. Kf5 g6+ 41. Kf4 { At least here, white has created 2 weaknesses to probe - starting with g4, if allowed. } 41... h5 $16) 39... Kd6 40. b3 b5 41. bxc4 Bxc4 42. a4 Kd5 43. axb5 Bxb5 44. Rf1?? { You hate to see it. } (44. Rh1!? Kc4 45. Kd2 Kd5 46. Rh5+ Kd6 { White's active rook should be enough to finally infiltrate and weaken the dark square kingside fortress. } (46... Kc4?? 47. Rc5+ Kb3 48. Rxb5+! { [%cal Gd4d5,Gd5d6,Gd6d7,Gd7d8] } 48... axb5 49. d5) 47. Rc5 $18) 44... Bxf1 $19 *


